{
  "method": "Build a feature-first, circuit-second pipeline that turns opaque activations into causal, human-auditable components. First, pick a target model layer (or short stack of layers) and collect activations over a diverse, held-out corpus. Learn a sparse dictionary over these activations with a reconstruction objective and strong sparsity, but stabilize and sharpen feature semantics by adding a prototype-anchoring head: each latent unit is encouraged to become the centroid of a tight, discriminative cluster in the activation space, and an auxiliary confidence head flags when a unit’s semantics are uncertain. The result is a monosemantic feature bank whose codes reconstruct the original activations while remaining highly sparse and cluster-aligned, providing candidate human-interpretable features.\n\nNext, map features to minimal circuits. For each discovered feature, identify upstream donors and downstream consumers by tracing gradients and weight-mediated influence to form an initial overcomplete subgraph. Prune it with hierarchical group-sparsity: iteratively apply group-lasso-style penalties over structured groups (e.g., neuron fan-in, fan-out, and layer-level groups) to drive most edges to zero while preserving the feature’s ability to reconstruct and affect the model’s logits. Alternate expansion (add the highest-residual contributors) and pruning steps until the subgraph stabilizes into a compact “circuitlet” that carries that feature’s computation.\n\nVerify the decomposition causally, not just correlationally. Perform activation and path patching: for matched input pairs where a feature is high vs low, interchange only the feature code (and, separately, only edges of its circuitlet) and measure Average Causal Effect on task outputs. To keep verification scalable, maintain a top-k set of suspected critical nodes/edges per feature and perform efficient pairwise checks among adjacent candidates, refining the ranking of important elements with near-linear cost rather than exhaustive all-pairs tests. In parallel, run layer-wise linear probes for the human-labeled concept linked to each feature to localize where the concept first emerges and where it is read out, and require that interventional effects and probe localization agree before accepting a feature–circuit match.\n\nHarden and document the results. Use the confidence head to gate claims: features with high uncertainty undergo extra testing on out-of-distribution and counterfactual datasets, plus negative-control interventions that should not change the output. Avoid model self-evaluation by relying on external references (held-out labels, perturbation-grounded metrics) and human spot checks only for borderline cases. Finally, publish a feature card for each accepted unit summarizing exemplars, counter-exemplars, causal effect sizes, upstream/downstream nodes, known failure modes, and safe edit directions. Edits are then applied by steering along a feature’s code or by weight surgery confined to its verified circuitlet and are re-validated with the same interventional tests before deployment.",
  "rationale": "Sparse, prototype-anchored dictionary learning turns dense activations into a small set of monosemantic codes that are easier to name and edit, while an uncertainty head helps avoid overclaiming when features are entangled. Hierarchical, group-sparse pruning converts diffuse influence maps into compact, testable circuitlets aligned to how parameters are organized, yielding minimal explanations that survive ablations.\n\nCausal verification via interchanges and activation/path patching ensures that the proposed features and circuits are not just predictive but mechanistically necessary or sufficient for the behavior. Efficient pairwise refinement makes these tests scalable, and layer-wise linear probes triangulate where concepts live, offering a second, independent check. Guarding against self-evaluation bias with reference-based metrics and negative controls reduces the risk of falsely validating spurious decompositions.",
